import{_ as s,C as i,o as t,c as l,ah as o,b as n,w as a,a as d,E as h,ai as p}from"./chunks/framework.C8Zd3T50.js";const c="/BhoW6b/login.jpg",u="/BhoW6b/urlPrivacy.jpg",b=JSON.parse('{"title":"A New Operating System","description":"","frontmatter":{},"headers":[],"relativePath":"architecture.md","filePath":"architecture.md"}'),f={name:"architecture.md"};function A(g,e,m,y,v,w){const r=i("Mermaid");return t(),l("div",null,[e[1]||(e[1]=o('<h1 id="a-new-operating-system" tabindex="-1">A New Operating System <a class="header-anchor" href="#a-new-operating-system" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;A New Operating System&quot;">​</a></h1><p>os384 allows you to write general purpose software that is genuinely private, secure, and and respects a user&#39;s sovereignty. That has simply not been possible before.</p><p>os384 runs partly on your devices, and partly on our servers – or on those of another vendor or your own servers. It&#39;s open source and not tied to any specific vendor. Key management and in fact all user-related information is handled client side, not by us or any other central authority.</p><p>Initial implementation of os384 is entirely in Typescript (ES2022). A simple starting point as a developer is to look at writing simple web apps. Key libraries are:</p><ul><li><p>lib384 code (ESM): <a href="https://c3.384.dev/api/v2/page/7938Nx0wM39T/384.esm.js" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">https://c3.384.dev/api/v2/page/7938Nx0wM39T/384.esm.js</a></p></li><li><p>lib384 types: <a href="https://c3.384.dev/api/v2/page/u2d23u7w/lib384.d.ts" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">https://c3.384.dev/api/v2/page/u2d23u7w/lib384.d.ts</a></p></li><li><p>lib384 code (IIFE): <a href="https://c3.384.dev/api/v2/page/L2w00jf4/384.iife.js" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">https://c3.384.dev/api/v2/page/L2w00jf4/384.iife.js</a></p></li></ul><p>Most documents related to 384 are actually distributed as PDFs hosted on os384, or as &quot;os384 apps&quot; (including the &quot;whitepaper&quot; you are reading now). These aren&#39;t &quot;served&quot; from 384.dev in the conventional sense, instead, 384.dev will run what we call the &quot;loader&quot; in your browser.</p><h2 id="the-loader" tabindex="-1">The Loader <a class="header-anchor" href="#the-loader" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;The Loader&quot;">​</a></h2><p>If you go to <a href="https://384.dev" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">https://384.dev</a>, you will see a screen like below. This corresponds to &quot;logging in&quot;, but is entirely local. It will ask for a &quot;<a href="/BhoW6b/glossary.html#strongpin">strongpin</a>&quot; (essentially a username) and a passphrase. Or if you&#39;re setting things up from scratch, you can provide a <a href="/BhoW6b/glossary.html#storage-token">storage token</a> and create a new setup (or &quot;<a href="/BhoW6b/glossary.html#wallet">wallet</a>&quot;) We&#39;ll go into more details on all this later. For now, we&#39;re just going to introduce the &quot;loader&quot; concept.</p><figure style="text-align:center;" align="center"><img src="'+c+'" width="40%" alt="Login Screen"><figcaption>https://384.dev</figcaption></figure><p>We will get back to the &quot;top level&quot; later. For now, try going to <a href="https://384.dev/#A1cQwk" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">https://384.dev/#A1cQwk</a>. Click it, see what happens, and come back here.</p><p>You should have seen a PDF with a presentation about some aspects of the storage system of os384, contrasted with other systems. But, crucially, our server had no idea that this was a PDF. Note the URL, what&#39;s that &quot;#A1cQwk&quot; part?</p><p>Let&#39;s remind ourselves of what URLs are:</p><figure style="text-align:center;" align="center"><img src="'+u+'" width="70%" alt="Login Screen"><figcaption>Levels of Sensitivity</figcaption></figure><p>The diagram above illustrates the level of privacy leakage that occurs in common use of the web. With a secured connection (the &quot;S&quot; in HTTPS), the only thing leaked is the domain name. But the server itself of course sees the entire URL.</p><p>The &quot;#A1cQwk&quot; part is called a &quot;fragment identifier&quot; (or more technically a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/URI_fragment" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">URI fragment</a>). It&#39;s not transmitted over the network, it&#39;s just used by the browser, typically to navigate to a specific part of the page. But it can also be used for sensitive information such as keys or identifiers.</p><p>When you go to 384.dev, what happens is that your browser loads os384, more specifically what we call &quot;loader&quot;. It&#39;s essentially a microkernel, a virtual machine manager (VMM), and a bootloader all in one.</p><p>The loader only runs inside your browser. It doesn&#39;t need to be served from 384.dev, you can run it locally.</p><p>What the loader will do as it spins up depends on what URL you went to. In the case of 384.dev/#A1cQwk, it will interpret &quot;A1cQwk&quot; as a shortened name to a &quot;Page&quot;, our equivalent of a url shortener.</p><p>We won&#39;t cover Pages in detail yet, but they are associated with Channels, and served with one of the api endpoints of Channels.</p><p>In this case, it will see that the page is a PDF, and that&#39;s a data format that is safe to serve directly to the user.</p><p>For more complicated cases, with fully functioning web apps, they are not safe to run at the &quot;top level&quot; of 384.dev, instead they are served from a subdomain of 384.dev. The loader will pick a random subdomain, in order to obscure from DNS or any other monitoring what the contents are.</p><p>These whitepapers are such a case. This diagram hopefully helps:</p>',22)),(t(),n(p,null,{default:a(()=>[h(r,{id:"mermaid-78",class:"mermaid",graph:"flowchart%20TB%0A%20%20%20%20%25%25%20Define%20the%20subgraphs%2Fclusters%0A%20%20%20%20subgraph%20StorageServers%5B%22Storage%20Servers%22%5D%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20style%20StorageServers%20fill%3Awhite%2Cstroke%3A%23666666%2Cstroke-width%3A2px%2Ccolor%3A%23333333%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20Shards%5BShards%5D%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20style%20Shards%20fill%3A%23add8e6%2Ccolor%3A%23333333%0A%20%20%20%20end%0A%20%20%20%20%0A%20%20%20%20subgraph%20Loader%5B%22Loader%22%5D%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20style%20Loader%20fill%3Awhite%2Cstroke%3A%23666666%2Cstroke-width%3A2px%2Ccolor%3A%23333333%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20LoaderNode%5B%22Loader%5Cn(384.dev)%22%5D%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20style%20LoaderNode%20fill%3A%23ffff99%2Ccolor%3A%23333333%0A%20%20%20%20end%0A%20%20%20%20%0A%20%20%20%20subgraph%20AppComponents%5B%22Application%20Components%22%5D%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20style%20AppComponents%20fill%3Awhite%2Cstroke%3A%23666666%2Cstroke-width%3A2px%2Ccolor%3A%23333333%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20FileSet%5B%22FileSet%5Cn(Static%20Site%20Package)%22%5D%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20VirtualFS%5B%22Virtual%20File%20System%20(SBFS)%22%5D%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20ServiceWorker%5B%22Service%20Worker%22%5D%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20Documentation%5B%22Official%20Documentation%5Cn(this%20static%20site)%22%5D%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20style%20FileSet%20fill%3A%23ffff99%2Ccolor%3A%23333333%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20style%20VirtualFS%20fill%3A%23ffff99%2Ccolor%3A%23333333%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20style%20ServiceWorker%20fill%3A%23ffff99%2Ccolor%3A%23333333%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20style%20Documentation%20fill%3A%23ffff99%2Ccolor%3A%23333333%0A%20%20%20%20end%0A%0A%20%20%20%20subgraph%20ChannelServers1%5B%22Channel%20Server%22%5D%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20style%20ChannelServers1%20fill%3Awhite%2Cstroke%3A%23666666%2Cstroke-width%3A2px%2Ccolor%3A%23333333%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20LoaderCode%5B%22loader%20code%20(index.js)%5CnURL%3A%20%2Fapi%2Fv2%2Fpage%2FrfD2ky75%22%5D%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20style%20LoaderCode%20fill%3A%23add8e6%2Ccolor%3A%23333333%0A%20%20%20%20end%0A%20%20%20%20%0A%20%20%20%20subgraph%20ChannelServers2%5B%22Channel%20Server%22%5D%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20style%20ChannelServers2%20fill%3Awhite%2Cstroke%3A%23666666%2Cstroke-width%3A2px%2Ccolor%3A%23333333%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20Lib384Code%5B%22lib384%20code%20(384.esm.js)%5CnURL%3A%20%2Fapi%2Fv2%2Fpage%2F7938Nx0wM39T%22%5D%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20%20%20style%20Lib384Code%20fill%3A%23add8e6%2Ccolor%3A%23333333%0A%20%20%20%20end%0A%0A%20%20%20%20%25%25%20Define%20the%20connections%0A%20%20%20%20FileSet%20--%3E%20VirtualFS%0A%20%20%20%20VirtualFS%20--%3E%20ServiceWorker%0A%20%20%20%20ServiceWorker%20--%3E%20Documentation%0A%20%20%20%20%0A%20%20%20%20%25%25%20Create%20separate%20nodes%20for%20edge%20labels%20with%20no%20background%0A%20%20%20%20EncData%5B%2F%22encrypted%20data%22%2F%5D%0A%20%20%20%20LaunchesLabel%5B%2F%22launches%22%2F%5D%0A%20%20%20%20ProvidesCode1%5B%2F%22provides%20code%22%2F%5D%0A%20%20%20%20ProvidesCode2%5B%2F%22provides%20code%22%2F%5D%0A%20%20%20%20DocumentsLabel%5B%2F%22documents%22%2F%5D%0A%20%20%20%20style%20EncData%20fill%3Anone%2Cstroke%3Anone%2Ccolor%3A%23333333%0A%20%20%20%20style%20LaunchesLabel%20fill%3Anone%2Cstroke%3Anone%2Ccolor%3A%23333333%0A%20%20%20%20style%20ProvidesCode1%20fill%3Anone%2Cstroke%3Anone%2Ccolor%3A%23333333%0A%20%20%20%20style%20ProvidesCode2%20fill%3Anone%2Cstroke%3Anone%2Ccolor%3A%23333333%0A%20%20%20%20style%20DocumentsLabel%20fill%3Anone%2Cstroke%3Anone%2Ccolor%3A%23333333%0A%20%20%20%20%0A%20%20%20%20%25%25%20Connect%20with%20dotted%20lines%0A%20%20%20%20Shards%20-.-%3E%20EncData%20-.-%3E%20FileSet%0A%20%20%20%20LoaderNode%20-.-%3E%20LaunchesLabel%20-.-%3E%20FileSet%0A%20%20%20%20LoaderCode%20-.-%3E%20ProvidesCode1%20-.-%3E%20LoaderNode%0A%20%20%20%20Lib384Code%20-.-%3E%20ProvidesCode2%20-.-%3E%20VirtualFS%0A%20%20%20%20Documentation%20-.-%3E%20DocumentsLabel%20-.-%3E%20Lib384Code%0A%20%20%20%20%0A%20%20%20%20%25%25%20Style%20for%20all%20connections%0A%20%20%20%20linkStyle%20default%20stroke%3A%23333333%2Ccolor%3A%23333333%0A%20%20%20%20%25%25%20Style%20for%20dotted%20connections%0A%20%20%20%20linkStyle%203%2C4%2C5%2C6%2C7%2C8%2C9%2C10%2C11%2C12%20stroke%3A%23333333%2Ccolor%3A%23333333%2Cstroke-dasharray%3A3%0A"})]),fallback:a(()=>[...e[0]||(e[0]=[d(" Loading... ",-1)])]),_:1})),e[2]||(e[2]=o('<ul><li><p>The loader is served off 384.dev. The code for the loader itself is fetched from the &quot;Page&quot; api of a channel server.</p></li><li><p>The loader sees a link to a <a href="/BhoW6b/glossary.html#shard">shard</a>, which it fetches and interprets. In this case, it contains a <a href="/BhoW6b/glossary.html#fileset">FileSet</a> (this whitepaper).</p></li><li><p>The loader launches a subdomain in a separate tab, and sets up a virtual file system. The code for this is also in lib384, which is also served as a Page.</p></li><li><p>That virtual file system (<a href="/BhoW6b/glossary.html#sbfs-os384-virtual-file-system">SBFS</a>) sets up a <a href="/BhoW6b/glossary.html#service-worker">service worker</a>, which will fetch, decrypt, and serve any components of the site (such as this html page)</p></li><li><p>The &quot;app&quot; that&#39;s being served is the documentation that you would use to develop all the parts of the system.</p></li></ul>',1))])}const k=s(f,[["render",A]]);export{b as __pageData,k as default};
